WEBVTT

00:00:00.430 --> 00:00:10.870
Hello and welcome back. In this lesson, I will show you how to use the skills that we created in the previous lesson.

00:00:12.010 --> 00:00:19.210
And if you remember, we saved the skill in this folder called AI skills. And this is the skill.

00:00:19.210 --> 00:00:30.550
So, in this exercise, we are going to use this skill to do reverse engineering on another CrackMe,

00:00:30.550 --> 00:00:40.750
and we are going to use this CrackMe client and the server. So, let us first run this and see

00:00:40.750 --> 00:00:50.530
how it works. We will run the activation server, and we will click Start. Then we

00:00:50.530 --> 00:00:59.700
will run the client, so the client will connect to the server. So, make sure you

00:00:59.700 --> 00:01:04.780
use the correct version of the client for the activation server, which is 32-

00:01:04.780 --> 00:01:12.180
bit. You need to use the 32-bit client. If you are using the activation server, which is

00:01:12.180 --> 00:01:19.320
64-bit, then make sure you also use the corresponding 64-bit client. In this

00:01:19.320 --> 00:01:26.520
exercise, I am using the 32-bit. So, that is why I ran the 32-bit activation

00:01:26.520 --> 00:01:35.140
server and the corresponding 32-bit client. So, here is how it works. When the

00:01:35.140 --> 00:01:40.660
client starts, it will ask you to enter a serial number. Let's say I enter

00:01:40.660 --> 00:01:49.900
something which is wrong, and then I click Activate. It tells me, "Wrong serial."

00:01:49.900 --> 00:01:56.280
So what happens behind the scenes is that the client connects to the server

00:01:56.280 --> 00:02:01.560
over the network. In this case, both are on the same network, same computer. We are

00:02:01.560 --> 00:02:10.220
simulating a server activation system, and so when a client sends this serial

00:02:10.220 --> 00:02:15.600
number to the server, the server will check it and then return whether it's

00:02:15.600 --> 00:02:21.020
correct or wrong. So when the client receives the message that the number

00:02:21.020 --> 00:02:27.320
that was sent is wrong, it will then pop up the error message, "Wrong serial." So

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:34.340
this simulates the actual scenario where you install software, and then when you

00:02:34.340 --> 00:02:39.380
want to activate or register, your software will connect to the Internet to

00:02:39.380 --> 00:02:45.920
connect to the activation server on the Internet. So, to make this a realistic

00:02:45.920 --> 00:02:52.220
experience, we will assume that this activation server is also not within our

00:02:52.220 --> 00:02:56.420
reach. We are not going to hack the activation server. So we are going to

00:02:56.420 --> 00:03:00.920
crack the client because the client is on our machine. So we assume this

00:03:00.920 --> 00:03:05.660
activation server is somewhere on the Internet. So I hope that clarifies the

00:03:05.660 --> 00:03:14.840
scenario of this exercise. So, now we are going to fire up our Codex, so let's

